ng for summer/early autumn harvest before winter. Excellent for pickling, stir-fries, and fresh use. Stores for shorter periods (3-4 months max). Ideal for continuous cropping systems. Less fibrous makes it easier to prepare and digest.", "availability": "Seasonal availability at farmers markets, Asian grocers; grow from any ginger variety harvested early"}, {"name": "Native Ginger (Alpinia caerulea) 🌱", "slug": "native-ginger-alpinia-caerulea", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 3, "origin": "Indigenous to Queensland and northern NSW rainforests; 50,000+ years of traditional use", "traits": "Grows 1-2m tall, glossy sword-shaped leaves, white fragrant flowers, bright blue berries", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate yield of edible shoots and abundant berry production", "growing_notes": "INDIGENOUS AUSTRALIAN SPECIES. Perfectly adapted to Humid subtropical subtropical climate. Grows naturally in Queensland''s coastal rainforests. Excellent for erosion control and bush tucker gardens. Tolerates full sun to full shade. Very hardy once established. Dies back in cool climates but evergreen in humid subtropical climates. Cultural significance to Indigenous Australians. Used traditionally for medicinal and culinary purposes.", "availability": "The Seed Collection, Australian Plants Online, native plant nurseries throughout Queensland"}, {"name": "Rio de Janeiro", "slug": "rio-de-janeiro", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 4, "origin": "Brazil (introduced variety); widely adopted in tropical/subtropical regions since 1900s", "traits": "Bold, large rhizomes with prominent fingers, buff-colored skin", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Very high yielding (25-35 tonnes/hectare)", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Yellow Ginger (Hedychium flavescens)", "slug": "yellow-ginger-hedychium-flavescens", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 5, "origin": "Native to Himalayas, Northern Vietnam, Sichuan; naturalized in Australia", "traits": "Short stem with tufted leaves, short thick rhizomes, ornamental yellow flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate rhizome production, valued more for flowers than roots", "growing_notes": "Adapts well to Humid subtropical subtropical environment. Primarily grown as ornamental but has medicinal applications. Used as analgesic for muscle pain, anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial properties. Prefers partial shade and consistent moisture. Flowers attract pollinators. Can become invasive in ideal conditions - plant responsibly.", "availability": "Bambooland, ornamental ginger specialists, subtropical plant nurseries"}, {"name": "Blue Hawaiian Ginger", "slug": "blue-hawaiian-ginger", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 6, "origin": "Brazil (native); cultivated in Hawaii and other subtropical regions", "traits": "Grows up to 3 feet tall, shiny green leaves, distinctive blue/purple hues in mature rhizomes", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate yield, ornamental and culinary value", "growing_notes": "Suitable for Humid subtropical subtropical climate with temperature range 15-27°C ideal. Cannot tolerate direct sun - burns easily, requires shade or dappled light. Rich in iron, sodium, vitamins A and C. Antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. Requires regular fertilization. Good for containers or shaded garden beds. Blue coloration indicates high enzyme content (Zingibain).", "availability": "Specialty ginger nurseries, online tropical plant suppliers, limited availability in Australia"}, {"name": "Spring Ginger (Early Harvest)", "slug": "spring-ginger-early-harvest", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 7, "origin": "Early harvest stage of mature ginger varieties; traditional Asian practice", "traits": "Hand-like shape similar to mature ginger, plump and juicy with pink blush", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Medium yield at 5-6 month harvest", "growing_notes": "Perfect timing for Humid subtropical growing season - plant September, harvest February-March. Used in recipes with strong odors to neutralize unpleasant tastes. Excellent for fresh use. More tender than mature ginger but more developed than baby ginger. Good bridge crop between baby and mature ginger. Requires consistent watering during Humid subtropical hot summer.", "availability": "Harvest timing of standard ginger varieties; available at Asian markets seasonally"}, {"name": "Shampoo Ginger (Zingiber zerumbet)", "slug": "shampoo-ginger-zingiber-zerumbet", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 8, "origin": "Native to India, Southeast Asia; cultivated in Hawaii and Pacific Islands for millennia", "traits": "Grows 1-2m tall, pine cone-shaped flower heads release sudsy fluid when squeezed, red/orange bracts", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good rhizome production, abundant flower production", "growing_notes": "Thrives in Humid subtropical subtropical climate below 1500ft elevation. Bitter ginger root provides quick relief for indigestion and upset stomach. Traditionally used as natural shampoo, conditioner, and skin lotion. Spreads via shallow rhizomes to form dense stands. Requires semi-shady spot and consistent moisture. Cultural significance in Pacific Island communities. Flowers attractive for ornamental purposes.", "availability": "Tropical plant specialists, Hawaiian plant suppliers, can be propagated from wild rhizomes where naturalized"}, {"name": "White Ginger (Hedychium coronarium)", "slug": "white-ginger-hedychium-coronarium", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 9, "origin": "Native to India, China, Southeast Asia; naturalized in Queensland", "traits": "Large herbaceous plant 1-3m tall, showy white fragrant flowers, spreads via rhizomes", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Prolific growth, forms extensive thickets under favorable conditions", "growing_notes": "CAUTION: Potentially invasive in Humid subtropical subtropical climate. Forms dense mats of rhizomes near soil surface. Has naturalized and become environmental weed in wetter areas of SE Queensland. Can suppress native plant regeneration. Prefers moist habitats. If planting, use containers or monitor closely. Beautiful ornamental but aggressive spreader. Listed on environmental weed lists in some regions.", "availability": "Available but not recommended for open garden planting due to invasive nature; better for containers"}, {"name": "Torch Ginger (Etlingera elatior)", "slug": "torch-ginger-etlingera-elatior", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 10, "origin": "Native to Southeast Asia (Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand)", "traits": "Tall plant 3-4m, spectacular red/pink flower spikes up to 1m tall, ornamental value", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good flower production in warm climates", "growing_notes": "Can grow in Humid subtropical subtropical climate with frost protection. Needs warm position, partial shade. Usually deciduous in winter in humid subtropical climates. Whole plant is edible - fruits, seed pods, seeds, flower stems used in traditional Indonesian and Thai dishes. Requires space due to large size. Best in protected garden areas.", "availability": "Bambooland, tropical ginger specialists, requires special order"}, {"name": "Shell Ginger (Alpinia zerumbet)", "slug": "shell-ginger-alpinia-zerumbet", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 11, "origin": "Native to Eastern Asia (Japan, Taiwan, China)", "traits": "Ovate leaves with green stripes, grows 2-3m tall, clusters of pink buds, shell-like flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate leaf and rhizome production", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""},